1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,550
In this video, we're now going to plot numeric or quantitative variables.

2
00:00:05,550 --> 00:00:10,290
As always, we're going to start by importing the libraries we need,

3
00:00:10,290 --> 00:00:11,895
as well as the dataset.

4
00:00:11,895 --> 00:00:13,230
In this case,

5
00:00:13,230 --> 00:00:16,950
we'll continue by looking at the diamonds dataset we've used before.

6
00:00:16,950 --> 00:00:21,015
In particular, I now want to look at the x,

7
00:00:21,015 --> 00:00:24,480
y, and z width of a diamond.

8
00:00:24,480 --> 00:00:27,885
These are given in terms of millimeters.

9
00:00:27,885 --> 00:00:30,210
Now, to plot a histogram,

10
00:00:30,210 --> 00:00:34,785
matplotlib offers the hist function,

11
00:00:34,785 --> 00:00:41,100
like what we've seen before we pass in the dataset to a data variable and then we

12
00:00:41,100 --> 00:00:48,050
can explicitly say we want an x histogram looking at the x parameter.

13
00:00:48,050 --> 00:00:53,915
By default, matplotlib breaks the data into 10 bins,

14
00:00:53,915 --> 00:00:56,060
which is usually too few.

15
00:00:56,060 --> 00:00:59,765
In addition, the bin boundaries are not aligned with the tick marks.

16
00:00:59,765 --> 00:01:01,925
This is somewhat confusing.

17
00:01:01,925 --> 00:01:04,790
Despite that, we can see that this is

18
00:01:04,790 --> 00:01:10,040
a unimodal histogram with a slightly right-skewed distribution.

19
00:01:10,040 --> 00:01:12,335
But because of that number of bins,

20
00:01:12,335 --> 00:01:15,335
we just really can't get much else.

21
00:01:15,335 --> 00:01:21,905
To solve this, we really want to use the bin parameter for the hist function.

22
00:01:21,905 --> 00:01:26,000
The bin parameter can take an integer number of bins,

23
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:31,160
and then it will automatically break the axis in to that number of bins,

24
00:01:31,160 --> 00:01:33,600
in this case 25.

25
00:01:34,610 --> 00:01:39,690
We see that now we're getting more information.

26
00:01:39,690 --> 00:01:43,700
Also notice that if I remove the semicolon,

27
00:01:43,700 --> 00:01:48,380
we get the plotting objects which previously we had been ignoring.

28
00:01:48,380 --> 00:01:54,245
In this case, it is the actual binning array.

29
00:01:54,245 --> 00:02:01,770
Instead a better way would be to explicitly define the bins ourself.

30
00:02:01,820 --> 00:02:10,615
We can do that by using the numpy arange function to define the array of bin edges.

31
00:02:10,615 --> 00:02:18,265
Here, I'm going to make an array of width bin size 1/4 of a millimeter.

32
00:02:18,265 --> 00:02:22,890
Now the first argument for arange is the minimum value.

33
00:02:22,890 --> 00:02:27,550
Here is 0. The second argument, the maximum value.

34
00:02:27,550 --> 00:02:34,640
In this case, we ask for the maximum value of that column x.

35
00:02:34,760 --> 00:02:38,455
This third variable is the step size,

36
00:02:38,455 --> 00:02:41,290
in this case, 1/4 of a millimeter.

37
00:02:41,290 --> 00:02:45,350
Notice also that for the maximum value,

38
00:02:45,350 --> 00:02:47,690
I go one bin further.

39
00:02:47,690 --> 00:02:52,730
This is because the values generated by arange include the lower bound,

40
00:02:52,730 --> 00:02:55,145
but not the maximum value,

41
00:02:55,145 --> 00:02:56,480
not the upper bound,

42
00:02:56,480 --> 00:03:02,090
only those things that are strictly lower/ by so adding an extra step size,

43
00:03:02,090 --> 00:03:05,725
this means that all values can be represented in the chart.

44
00:03:05,725 --> 00:03:08,165
Now, I take

45
00:03:08,165 --> 00:03:14,225
this variable bins and pass it into the parameter bins of the histogram function.

46
00:03:14,225 --> 00:03:17,960
Now I see something like this.

47
00:03:17,960 --> 00:03:21,410
Now we see that the data is approximately unimodal,

48
00:03:21,410 --> 00:03:25,955
safe for a bit of a dip in these 7-8 millimeter range.

49
00:03:25,955 --> 00:03:32,150
Now, what happens if we try an extremely small bin size like 1?

50
00:03:32,150 --> 00:03:36,920
On the one hand, this bin size is perhaps a bit too small,

51
00:03:36,920 --> 00:03:39,305
introducing a lot of noise.

52
00:03:39,305 --> 00:03:42,500
On the other hand, it does a good job of showing that

53
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:46,685
many diamonds are probably rounded to some nearest value.

54
00:03:46,685 --> 00:03:50,995
Seaborne also has a function for creating histograms.

55
00:03:50,995 --> 00:03:52,980
This is called histplot,

56
00:03:52,980 --> 00:03:56,070
and it works just like matplotlib.

57
00:03:56,070 --> 00:03:57,675
A couple of things.

58
00:03:57,675 --> 00:04:02,060
One, you'll notice the default bin count is larger than matplotlib.

59
00:04:02,060 --> 00:04:07,840
Second, if you'd like to normalize it to show the percent of each bin to the whole,

60
00:04:07,840 --> 00:04:12,970
you can pass in a parameter stat, short-course statistic.

61
00:04:12,970 --> 00:04:20,225
Then this shows you the total proportion of each bin to the whole.

62
00:04:20,225 --> 00:04:26,165
One other thing that might be of interest is there's parameter kde = True.

63
00:04:26,165 --> 00:04:32,550
This adds a kernel density estimate on top of the plot.

64
00:04:32,550 --> 00:04:35,330
A KDE is an estimate of the density of

65
00:04:35,330 --> 00:04:40,460
the data distribution and the total area underneath the curve is set to 1.

66
00:04:40,460 --> 00:04:42,605
If you're interested in this plot,

67
00:04:42,605 --> 00:04:47,280
you can read up about it more at the extras at the end of this lesson.

